==Project structure== {{multiple image | width = 150 | direction = vertical | align = right | footer = Sagan-Zaba Excavations | image1 = | alt1 = General view of Sagan-Zaba | caption1 = General view | image2 = BaikalArchFigure10aS-Zfinds.jpg | alt2 = Archaeological finds from Saga-Zaba | caption2 = Archaeological finds | image3 = BaikalArchFigure10bS-Zfinds.jpg | alt3 = Archaeological finds from Saga-Zaba | caption3 = Archaeological finds | image4 = BaikalArchFigure10cS-Zfinds.jpg | alt4 = Archaeological finds from Saga-Zaba | caption4 = Archaeological finds }}
The work of the Baikal Archaeology Project is organized within five research modules – Archaeology, Human Bioarchaeology, Human Genetics, Ethnoarchaeology, and Paleoenvironment – each addressing the Project’s general objectives with a different, but complementary, methodology. The Archaeology, Human Bioarchaeology, and Human Genetics modules supply the primary data on the Middle Holocene hunter-gatherers, while the Paleoenvironment and Ethnoarchaeology modules provide a broad interpretive framework for the bioarchaeological data.
The [https://web.archive.org/web/20090302032009/http://baikal.arts.ualberta.ca/about/archaeological.php Archaeology Module] examines development, use, and spatial organization of the region’s numerous hunter-gatherer cemeteries, mortuary protocols, social and political organization, migrations and mobility patterns, as well as the overall spatiotemporal variability in hunter-gatherer adaptations.<ref name="Bazaliiskii and Savel'ev 2003">[http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/077/Ant0770020.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121223050602/http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/077/Ant0770020.htm |date=2012-12-23 }}, '''Bazaliiskii, V. I., Savel’ev, N. A.''' 2003. The Wolf of Baikal: The “Lokomotiv” Early Neolithic Cemetery in Siberia (Russia). ''Antiquity'', vol. 77(295): 20–30.</ref><ref name="Goriunova and Weber 2003">'''Goriunova, O.I., Weber, A.W.''' 2003. Burial Complex with an Openwork Pendant from the Burial of Bronze Age Cemetery Кurma XI (Lake Baikal)]. ''Archeology, Ethnography and Anthropology of Eurasia'', vol. 4(16): 110–115.</ref><ref name="Haverkort et al. 2008">[http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6WH8-4R0CR3Y-1&_user=10&_coverDate=05/31/2008&_rdoc=15&_fmt=high&_orig=browse&_srch=doc-info(%23toc%236844%232008%23999649994%23683482%23FLA%23display%23Volume)&_cdi=6844&_sort=d&_docanchor=&_ct=29&_acct=C000050221&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=10&md5=1b151866faab5161b6fe6b39379263d1], Haverkort, C., '''Weber, A.W., Katzenberg, M.A., Goriunova, O.I.''', Simonetti, A., Creaser, R.A. 2008. Hunter-Gatherer Mobility Strategies and Resource Use Based on Strontium Isotope (87Sr/86Sr) Analysis: A Case Study from Middle Holocene Lake Baikal, Siberia. ''Journal of Archaeological Science'', vol. 35(5): 1265–1280.</ref><ref name="Weber 1995">[http://www.springerlink.com/content/k667127158gku15r/?p=11c28c489cac4c558fd900c615ee2d25&pi=2], '''Weber A.W.''' 1995. The Neolithic and Early Bronze Age of the Lake Baikal region, Siberia: A Review of Recent Research. ''