c3cc716f0a63757e1c13de33d0f2], '''White, D., Preece, R.C., Shchetnikov, A.A.''', Parfitt, S.A., Dlussky, K.G. 2008. A Holocene Molluscan Succession from Floodplain Sediments of the Upper Lena River Valley (Lake Baikal Region), Siberia. ''Quaternary Science Reviews'', vol. 27(9-10): 962–87.</ref> While this change is believed to be the most significant in the region's entire Holocene climate history, it appears that its impact may have been greatest on the semi-arid areas south and east of Lake Baikal rather than on the more forested west and north.
[https://web.archive.org/web/20090302032948/http://baikal.arts.ualberta.ca/about/ethnographic.php Ethnographic and ethnohistoric] research focuses upon how indigenous Buriat, Evenki, and Sakha peoples have adapted to boreal environments in general, and its coastal, alpine, and steppe niches in particular.<ref name="Anderson 2006 Norwegian Archaeological Review">[http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a748016227],'''Anderson, D.G.''' 2006. Dwellings, Storage and Summer Site Structure among Siberian Orochen Evenkis: Hunter-Gatherer Vernacular Architecture under Post-Socialist Conditions. ''Norwegian Archaeological Review'', vol. 39(1): 1–26. [http://www.informaworld.com/smpp/content~db=all~content=a769868062], Comments and Discussion in vol. 39(2): 162–71</ref> The module has also discovered, in 11 Siberian cities, a series of documents from the 1926 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110706205908/http://www.baikal.arts.ualberta.ca/polarcensus/ Polar Census] in Siberia, which is the richest dataset on boreal hunter-gatherers yet known.<ref name="Anderson n.d.">'''Anderson, D.G.''' (ed.). n.d. ''The 1926/27 Soviet Polar Census Expeditions: The Identity, Ethnography and Demography of Siberian Peoples''. Oxford: Berghahn Press. Forthcoming.</ref><ref name="Anderson 2006 Sibirica">[http://berghahn.publisher.ingentaconnect.com/content/berghahn/sibiric/2006/00000005/00000001/art00003] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130104053115/http://berghahn.publisher.ingentaconnect.com/content/berghahn/sibiric/2006/00000005/00000001/art00003 |date=2013-01-04 }},'''Anderson, D.G.''' 2006. The Turukhansk Polar Census Expedition of 1926/27 at the Crossroads of Two Scientific Traditions. ''Sibirica'', vol. 5(1): 24–61.</ref> {{-}}
==Fieldwork and field schools== [[File:BaikalArchFigure2bSites.jpg|thumb|left|Map of the Baikal region with location of archaeological fieldwork sites.]]{{multiple image | width = 100 | align = right | footer = Khuzhir-Nuge XIV Cemetery Excavations | image1 = BaikalArchFigure5KN14Generalview.jpg | alt1 = General view of the Khuzhir-Nuge XIV cemetery | caption1 = General view | image2 = BaikalArchFigure6aKN14BAgrave.jpg | alt2 = Bronze Age graves from Kuzhir Nuge XIV | caption2 = Bronze Age graves | image3 = BaikalArchFigure6bKN14BAgrave.jpg | alt3 = Bronze Age grave goods from Kuzhir Nuge XIV | caption3 = Bronze Age grave goods }} Researchers of the Archaeology, Paleoenvironment, and Ethnoarchaeology modules have conducted intensive fieldwork in many locations around Lake Baikal. Archaeologists excavated the cemeteries of Shamanka, Khuzhir-Nuge XIV, and Kurma XI, all located on the shores of Lake Baikal. This work expanded the existing collection of Middle Holocene burials in the region by c. 300 individuals, thus creating new research opportunities. Excavations were also carried out at the stratified habitation sites of Gorelyi Les in the Angara valley and Sagan-Zaba and Bugul’deika coves on Lake Baikal, providing archaeological data covering the entire Holocene. In conjunction with these excavations, the Baikal Archaeology Project organized archaeological field schools which attracted participants from Russia, Canada, USA, United Kingdom, and Poland.
'''Cemeteries'''
*K14: Khuzhir-Nuge XIV *KUR: Kurma XI *LOK: Lokomotiv *UID: Ust'-Ida *SHA: ShamankaII
'''Habitation Sites'''
*BUG: Bugul'deika *GL: Gorelyi Les *S-Z: Sagan-Zaba
{{-}} [[File:BaikalArchFigure11PaleoSites.jpg|thumb|left|Map of the Baikal region with location of paleoenvironmental fieldwork sites.]]{{multiple image | width = 150 | align = right | footer = Paleoenvironmental Studies | image1 = BaikalArchFigure13MolluskCollection.jpg | alt1 = Collection of modern molluscs in the Baikal region | caption1 = Collection of modern molluscs in the Baikal region | image2 = BaikalArchFigure14Mollusks.jpg | alt2 = Sample of modern molluscs from the Baikal region | caption2 = Sample of modern molluscs from the Baikal region | image3 = Fossil_Molluscs_Dustin_White.JPG | alt3 = Sample of fossil molluscs from the Baikal region | caption3 = Sample of fossil molluscs from the Baikal region }} The Paleonvironment module conducted fieldwork at numerous locations around Lake Baikal including its western shores (lakes Shara and Khall), the valleys of the Lena (Basovo), Selenga (Burdukovo), and Kirenga (Krasnyi Yar) rivers, the Tunka Valley (lake Arky) west of Baikal, and northern Mongolia. This work involved detailed examination of Holocene lake core records (pollen, diatom and macrofossils) and stratified floodplain sediments for high resolution paleoenvironmental reconstructions.
{{-}} [[File:BaikalArchFigure15EthnoSites.jpg|thumb|left|Map of the Baikal region with location of ethnographic and ethnoarchaeological fieldwork sites.]] {{multiple image | width = 150 | align = right | footer = Ethnoarchaeological Fieldwork | image1 = BaikalArchFigure16EthnoFieldworkVitim.jpg | alt1 = Ethnoarchaeological fieldwork in the upper Vitim Valley | caption1 = In the upper Vitim Valley | image2 = BaikalArchFigure17EthnoFieldworkZhuia.jpg | alt2 = Ethnoarchaeological fieldwork on the Zhuia River in the upper Lena drainage | caption2 = On the Zhuia River in the upper Lena drainage }} The Ethnoarchaeology module organized field research with Evenki and Sakha hunters and reindeer herders at sites in the Bodaibo District (Irkutsk oblast’), Zhuia River Valley, Severobaikalsk District (Buriat Republic), and villages of Essei and Olenok. This fieldwork is designed to provide the Baikal Archaeology Project with modern examples of subsistence action in specific lacustrian and riverine landscapes, characteristic also of the Middle Holocene hunter-gatherer groups. {{-}}
==Dissemination== The Baikal Archaeology Project has organized three international conferences (in Canada, Russia and Scotland), several conference sessions, and dozens of workshops and seminars. Project scholars and graduate students have produced numerous journalism papers, doctoral dissertations and masters’ theses, as well as five monographs under its Northern Hunter-Gatherers Research Series, published by [https://web.archive.org/web/20090804022325/http://www.uofaweb.ualberta.ca/polar/ Canadian Circumpolar Institute Press], University of Alberta. The most important publications are listed below.
